@flexiarg proof-search/extend-library-not-proof
@title When a Proof Stalls, Ask Whether the Library Is What's Missing
@sigils [📚/⇧]
@keywords stalled proof, missing lemma, mathlib, library extension, cross-problem impact, expected information gain, effort allocation
@audience anyone deciding where formalization effort goes next
@tone corrective
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a proof stalls at a missing piece, resist the instinct to grind that proof forward by local workarounds. First classify the blocker: is it PROOF-LOCAL (this argument needs a cleverer step) or a LIBRARY GAP (the ecosystem lacks a lemma/instance/tactic that many arguments need)? Library gaps are closed once and pay everywhere; local grinding pays once and teaches the library nothing.

  + context: Formalization effort is scarce and proofs stall constantly.
    The visible unit of progress is "my proof compiles," which biases
    effort toward local workarounds.

  + IF:
      A proof stalls at a missing lemma, instance, or tactic.

  + HOWEVER:
      Grinding the single proof forward IS possible — an inline lemma, a
      20-line workaround, a weaker statement — and feels like progress,
      while the same gap silently stalls other proofs in the corpus.

  + THEN:
      Check the gap against the corpus (the sorry-boundary atlas, or a
      search over other partials): if the missing piece would unblock
      more than this proof, promote it — state it at library generality,
      close it there, and let every blocked proof consume it. Only
      workaround locally when the gap is genuinely proof-local.

  + BECAUSE:
      Effort should flow to the highest cross-problem impact: the value
      of a library extension is the expected number of unblocked
      arguments (EIG over the corpus), while a local workaround's value
      is bounded by one. The library is the generative model; local
      workarounds are unshared observations.
      (Kin: [[proof-search/sorry-boundary-clustering]].)

  + canonical-instance:
      The M-diagramprover thesis in one line: rank Mathlib extensions by
      expected impact over the 489-problem prelim corpus rather than
      completing proofs one at a time — the readiness numbers (39
      partials, ~76 of ≥200 problems attempted) exist precisely to make
      this allocation computable. Authored as a proof-search seed
      2026-07-05.
